title: "Defining AI Agents: An Ontological and Topological Framework for Organizational Systems"
abstract: >-
  The scalability and governance challenges of AI agents trace back to a
  fundamental architectural deficit: the absence of an explicit, semantically
  expressive, and structurally adaptive abstraction layer. This paper introduces
  an architectural framework utilizing explicit, machine-readable ontological and
  topological representations for AI agents. Leveraging category theory,
  mereotopology, and graph theory, it formally defines the framework and proves
  five core properties: composability, interoperability, provenance preservation,
  auditability, and formal verifiability.
